00:00:29,100 --> 00:00:30,190
Jonathan?

8
00:00:30,190 --> 00:00:33,175
In 1978, there was the Household Responsibility System.

9
00:00:33,175 --> 00:00:33,790
Right.

10
00:00:33,790 --> 00:00:36,890
Which reintroduced private incentive into agriculture.

11
00:00:36,890 --> 00:00:42,190
It caused an increase in productivity, I think, from 1978 to 2007.

12
00:00:42,190 --> 00:00:47,980
The poverty declined from, like, 30.7% down to 1.6%.

13
00:00:47,980 --> 00:00:51,665
So huge declines, along with great increases in wages.

14
00:00:51,665 --> 00:00:52,370
Right.

15
00:00:52,370 --> 00:00:53,575
And that's really--

16
00:00:53,575 --> 00:00:55,080
productivity increased a lot.

17
00:00:55,080 --> 00:00:59,430
A huge part of that is a return-- this Household Responsibility

18
00:00:59,430 --> 00:01:03,140
System is another way of calling it-- calling family farming.

19
00:01:03,140 --> 00:01:07,360
Which had been the basic structure of Chinese farming forever.

20
00:01:07,360 --> 00:01:08,980
Or at least as far as we know.

21
00:01:08,980 --> 00:01:13,060
At least back to Tang, or back to Song period.

22
00:01:13,060 --> 00:01:16,160
So families taking care of their own.

23
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:19,800
What does Chinese agriculture look from that point toward today?

24
00:01:19,800 --> 00:01:20,830
Zack?

25
00:01:20,830 --> 00:01:22,332
It's like pseudo-privatized.

26
00:01:22,332 --> 00:01:23,540
So the land still is almost--

27
00:01:23,540 --> 00:01:24,289
Pseudo-privatized.

28
00:01:24,289 --> 00:01:25,230
That's a really good--

29
00:01:25,230 --> 00:01:25,321


30
00:01:25,321 --> 00:01:25,820
--good word.

31
00:01:25,820 --> 00:01:27,550
Yeah.

32
00:01:27,550 --> 00:01:31,870
--for all intents and purposes, it's treated as if it's privatized.

33
00:01:31,870 --> 00:01:34,410
The owners of the land can sublease their land.

34
00:01:34,410 --> 00:01:38,510
Above certain quotas, they're allowed to actually sell their extra produce

35
00:01:38,510 --> 00:01:39,700
on the market.

36
00:01:39,700 --> 00:01:43,150
So it essentially mirrors a basic market system,

37
00:01:43,150 --> 00:01:46,185
but there's some basic government intervention.

38
00:01:46,185 --> 00:01:47,330
Right.

39
00:01:47,330 --> 00:01:51,660
So it becomes, once again, a family-run-- and now,

40
00:01:51,660 --> 00:01:57,039
without landlords-- family-run, market-driven agricultural system

41
00:01:57,039 --> 00:01:57,955
that really takes off.

42
00:01:57,955 --> 00:02:04,830
An enormous boom in agricultural production, in the 1980s in particular.

43
00:02:04,830 --> 00:02:05,970
Nadia?

44
00:02:05,970 --> 00:02:10,650
And even though the government still controlled the land and owned it,

45
00:02:10,650 --> 00:02:13,620
but after meeting the production goal as these farmers

46
00:02:13,620 --> 00:02:19,090
could sell whatever excess they have at the market and gain profits.

47
00:02:19,090 --> 00:02:22,160
So that helped the poverty rate decrease.

48
00:02:22,160 --> 00:02:25,607
So in the '50s and '60s, there were quotas

49
00:02:25,607 --> 00:02:27,940
that the state could take whatever it wanted, basically.

50
00:02:27,940 --> 00:02:31,030
And did take everything in the late '50s and early '60s.

51
00:02:31,030 --> 00:02:35,290
By the late '70s and '80s, the state quotas decreased very markedly.

52
00:02:35,290 --> 00:02:38,580
There are still some, but you can market the rest.

53
00:02:38,580 --> 00:02:43,720
And increasingly, it becomes a privatized agricultural economy.

54
00:02:43,720 --> 00:02:45,860
You can invest in it.

55
00:02:45,860 --> 00:02:47,350
But again, do you own the land?

56
00:02:47,350 --> 00:02:50,360
Brian, if you're a farmer, and you've built up,

57
00:02:50,360 --> 00:02:52,630
in the 1980s, a wonderful plot.

58
00:02:52,630 --> 00:02:56,130
You're growing vegetables for downtown Shanghai.

59
00:02:56,130 --> 00:02:59,460
And now people in Shanghai have the money to pay more for good vegetables,

60
00:02:59,460 --> 00:03:01,720
and you can grow things, and so on.

61
00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:03,820
And you want your son to inherit it.

62
00:03:03,820 --> 00:03:04,820
What are his chances?

63
00:03:04,820 --> 00:03:06,176
It's up to the government.

64
00:03:06,176 --> 00:03:07,800
The government still owns it nominally.

65
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:11,150
And the person just works on it and has to make all the government--

66
00:03:11,150 --> 00:03:12,270
Right, you don't know.

67
00:03:12,270 --> 00:03:13,940
You really don't know.

68
00:03:13,940 --> 00:03:17,830
Your family has a contract to do it, up to decades.

69
00:03:17,830 --> 00:03:21,860
But you don't know for sure if your son-- who's likely to go to the city

70
00:03:21,860 --> 00:03:25,020
anyway, because he wants to get out, and see the world,

71
00:03:25,020 --> 00:03:28,160
and make more actual cash.

72
00:03:28,160 --> 00:03:30,870
But you don't know for sure.

73
00:03:30,870 --> 00:03:37,480
Rose-Ann, if I'm the government of X and Y township, and you have a farm,

74
00:03:37,480 --> 00:03:43,750
but I really would like to expand a road through your farm.

75
00:03:43,750 --> 00:03:45,130
What happens?

76
00:03:45,130 --> 00:03:47,480
Then you get to expand the road.

77
00:03:47,480 --> 00:03:49,265
I get to expand the road.

78
00:03:49,265 --> 00:03:51,945
And you get to move.

79
00:03:51,945 --> 00:03:53,486
And do you get compensated, Rose-Ann?

80
00:03:53,486 --> 00:03:54,340
Yeah.

81
00:03:54,340 --> 00:03:56,260
I think I do get compensated.

82
00:03:56,260 --> 00:03:59,480
But I think that the government has the say,

83
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:03,720
in terms of evaluating the compensation rate.

84
00:04:03,720 --> 00:04:08,060
Assuming that one knows, eventually, what the market price of this land

85
00:04:08,060 --> 00:04:12,960
will be, what percentage do you think you get of the ultimate market price?

86
00:04:12,960 --> 00:04:15,820
Once this land is built, the road goes through,

87
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:18,930
there are shopping malls on either side of it.

88
00:04:18,930 --> 00:04:20,610
Probably not a lot.

89
00:04:20,610 --> 00:04:21,484
Probably not a lot.

90
00:04:21,484 --> 00:04:22,400
Anybody want to guess?

91
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:23,280
Kennedy?

92
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:24,590
Can I ask a quick question?

93
00:04:24,590 --> 00:04:25,744
Sure.

94
00:04:25,744 --> 00:04:27,910
They talked about in the text how it was problematic

95
00:04:27,910 --> 00:04:31,076
that some people, like farmers, were selling their land to developers, which

96
00:04:31,076 --> 00:04:33,290
is then further decreasing the amount of arable land.

97
00:04:33,290 --> 00:04:33,790
Right.

98
00:04:33,790 --> 00:04:36,420
If a farmer sold the land to a developer,

99
00:04:36,420 --> 00:04:39,080
but then the government decided they wanted that plot of land,

100
00:04:39,080 --> 00:04:42,163
say, to build a highway or something, could they destroy that development?

101
00:04:42,163 --> 00:04:44,080
And who would be compensated?

102
00:04:44,080 --> 00:04:45,610
In that case, the developer.

103
00:04:45,610 --> 00:04:47,410
The developer would be compensated.

104
00:04:47,410 --> 00:04:49,870
And it's perfectly possible, because the government

105
00:04:49,870 --> 00:04:51,719
can take land more than once.

106
00:04:51,719 --> 00:04:53,260
After all, there's only so much land.

107
00:04:53,260 --> 00:04:57,030
And it's the largest source of income for local governments across China--

108
00:04:57,030 --> 00:04:58,930
are land sales and resales.

109
00:04:58,930 --> 00:05:03,080
But your farmer, your average-- and it's a statistic that is really

110
00:05:03,080 --> 00:05:06,080
quite stunning, and it seems to be getting higher--

111
00:05:06,080 --> 00:05:10,360
but in the last decade, so much farmland lost to development

112
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:13,860
by this kind of-- you know, my taking Rose-Ann's farm.

113
00:05:13,860 --> 00:05:19,690
You would get, on average, about 2% of the ultimate market value of land

114
00:05:19,690 --> 00:05:22,870
adjacent to large urban areas.

115
00:05:22,870 --> 00:05:25,350
And then you have nothing to do.

116
00:05:25,350 --> 00:05:28,410
So it's a very, very difficult situation.

117
00:05:28,410 --> 00:05:31,370
And it's one of the reasons why a lot of people are moving to cities.

118
00:05:31,370 --> 00:05:38,200
And Chinese agriculture is really under different kinds of stresses now.

119
00:05:38,200 --> 00:05:41,900
So this return to family farming is a huge boost to productivity.

120
00:05:41,900 --> 00:05:45,730
A one-time boost.

121
00:05:45,730 --> 00:05:49,060
But it still doesn't solve the issue of who

122
00:05:49,060 --> 00:05:53,220
invests in agriculture for the long haul.

