00:05:54,030 --> 00:05:56,691
I just have a quick question about-- I guess

125
00:05:56,691 --> 00:05:59,190
Johnathan was talking about how the return to family farming

126
00:05:59,190 --> 00:06:00,939
increased the productivity, because people

127
00:06:00,939 --> 00:06:03,620
could sell their excesses to the market.

128
00:06:03,620 --> 00:06:07,590
Right, and they could sell goods to go to real markets, yes.

129
00:06:07,590 --> 00:06:11,130
Rather than just by state plan.

130
00:06:11,130 --> 00:06:13,120
Why did the government still have the quotas?

131
00:06:13,120 --> 00:06:16,230
What were the-- the crops that were being grown with the quotas,

132
00:06:16,230 --> 00:06:17,854
where was that going?

133
00:06:17,854 --> 00:06:19,390
If there was also a market.

134
00:06:19,390 --> 00:06:23,290
So why would the government still have-- even, for example, a tax in grain,

135
00:06:23,290 --> 00:06:24,514
that you would pay in grain.

136
00:06:24,514 --> 00:06:25,430
Some percentage of it.

137
00:06:25,430 --> 00:06:26,638
Why would it still have this?

138
00:06:26,638 --> 00:06:30,350
As it would, until the late '80s, early '90s, in a significant way.

139
00:06:30,350 --> 00:06:32,350
Why do you think?

140
00:06:32,350 --> 00:06:34,694
It's a great question.

141
00:06:34,694 --> 00:06:36,860
And I don't know that there's only one answer to it.

142
00:06:36,860 --> 00:06:37,680
Zheyan?

143
00:06:37,680 --> 00:06:42,770
Maybe the revenue was going to industrialization during that period.

144
00:06:42,770 --> 00:06:45,990
So part of it is that agricultural productivity still

145
00:06:45,990 --> 00:06:50,487
pays for industrialization, which is still state run.

146
00:06:50,487 --> 00:06:52,570
Not much of it is exported by this period of time,

147
00:06:52,570 --> 00:06:54,790
but it was in the '50s and '60s.

148
00:06:54,790 --> 00:06:57,350
Probably another answer is that-- yeah, Nadia?

149
00:06:57,350 --> 00:07:01,680
Could it be, like, in the Tang system, where it's, sort of, renting the land?

150
00:07:01,680 --> 00:07:04,130
So they give them the land to use it, and that's

151
00:07:04,130 --> 00:07:11,050
what the farmers pay to the government in exchange for using the land.

152
00:07:11,050 --> 00:07:12,044
It is a kind of a rent.

153
00:07:12,044 --> 00:07:12,960
You're thinking right.

154
00:07:12,960 --> 00:07:15,060
You can think of-- all farmers are effectively

155
00:07:15,060 --> 00:07:16,940
sharecroppers in this regard.

156
00:07:16,940 --> 00:07:18,940
But the crops are shared with the state.

157
00:07:18,940 --> 00:07:20,410
Why does the state need them?

158
00:07:20,410 --> 00:07:23,160
Well, increasingly, it doesn't.

159
00:07:23,160 --> 00:07:26,960
But you know, governments change policy, sometimes pretty slowly.

160
00:07:26,960 --> 00:07:29,610
There were bureaucracies in place.

161
00:07:29,610 --> 00:07:32,180
How long has there been a land tax in China?

162
00:07:32,180 --> 00:07:34,440
This kind of tax in grain and so on?

163
00:07:34,440 --> 00:07:35,340
Jake?

164
00:07:35,340 --> 00:07:36,390
Centuries.

165
00:07:36,390 --> 00:07:37,910
Over two millennia.

166
00:07:37,910 --> 00:07:38,519
Two millennia?

167
00:07:38,519 --> 00:07:39,310
Over two millennia.

168
00:07:39,310 --> 00:07:40,101
Over two millennia.

169
00:07:40,101 --> 00:07:41,449
How many millennia?

170
00:07:41,449 --> 00:07:41,990
I don't know.

171
00:07:41,990 --> 00:07:42,960
2.5.

172
00:07:42,960 --> 00:07:43,510
2.5.

173
00:07:43,510 --> 00:07:44,509
That's a great question.

174
00:07:44,509 --> 00:07:46,720
But I have no idea.

175
00:07:46,720 --> 00:07:47,912
Probably about 2.5.

176
00:07:47,912 --> 00:07:48,870
At least two millennia.

177
00:07:48,870 --> 00:07:51,590
Yeah, I think so.

178
00:07:51,590 --> 00:07:53,220
2,600.

179
00:07:53,220 --> 00:07:55,770
So you were oh, so close.

180
00:07:55,770 --> 00:07:58,650
OK, and does China have a land tax today?

181
00:07:58,650 --> 00:07:59,970
Henry, what do you think?

182
00:07:59,970 --> 00:08:01,480
Does China have a land tax today?

183
00:08:01,480 --> 00:08:03,185
No agriculture tax.

184
00:08:03,185 --> 00:08:08,100
It was meant as a measure to relieve farmers of some burden,

185
00:08:08,100 --> 00:08:12,270
especially inequality between rural and urban citizens.

186
00:08:12,270 --> 00:08:14,700
So no agriculture tax.

187
00:08:14,700 --> 00:08:19,780
For the first time-- not just in memory, but as far as we can tell, in history--

188
00:08:19,780 --> 00:08:21,820
there is no agricultural tax.

189
00:08:21,820 --> 00:08:24,905
That is, the taxing of agricultural goods going to the state.

190
00:08:24,905 --> 00:08:26,780
And this was abolished by Premier Wen Jiabao.

191
00:08:26,780 --> 00:08:28,810
A great reform, actually.

192
00:08:28,810 --> 00:08:32,580
I think in 2006.

193
00:08:32,580 --> 00:08:35,980
Now what it's like to be a Chinese farmer today?

194
00:08:35,980 --> 00:08:37,770
Is it a good life?

195
00:08:37,770 --> 00:08:38,270
Michael?

196
00:08:38,270 --> 00:08:41,192
Well, it seems like there's a lot of migration to cities.

197
00:08:41,192 --> 00:08:44,584
But they don't have a hukou, and so a lot of migrant workers,

198
00:08:44,584 --> 00:08:52,050
in cities like Shenzhen, who don't have the same health care and schooling

199
00:08:52,050 --> 00:08:54,040
and financial benefits.

200
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:56,394
And so it's sort of, like, an awkward position.

201
00:08:56,394 --> 00:08:58,852
And it seems like a lot of the older people within families

202
00:08:58,852 --> 00:09:01,420
are, sort of, staying behind in the rural areas.

203
00:09:01,420 --> 00:09:06,880
So what kind of social benefits do farmers have already in China?

204
00:09:06,880 --> 00:09:10,670


